<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Bonn ignores EC cereals limit in eastern Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BONN government is refusing to abide by European Community limits on the
amount of land which can be sown with cereals in eastern Germany,
threatening a bruising row between Germany and the EC at a meeting of
agriculture ministers today.
A senior Commission official said Bonn's militancy on agriculture threatened
to unravel the Common Agricultural Policy reform, break budgetary limits
Bonn is constantly urging on Brussels, and further complicate General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade talks already on the brink over the farm
issue.
The dispute was ignited because the east German Lander, or states, have
exceeded by nearly 10 per cent the area they are entitled to plant. Under
last year's reform of the CAP, which introduced big price cuts and
production restraints to rein in oversupply, budgetary outlays, and to try
to make possible a Gatt farm trade agreement, the former east Germany was
given a 'base area' eligible for EC price support of 3.6m hectares. This has
been overshot by 347,000 hectares.
The Commission, interpreting the rules flexibly to take account of the
prostration of the eastern German economy, on Friday proposed a gradual
phasing in of the automatic penalties for exceeding the planted area.
Brussels proposes that instead of facing a 10 per cent reduction in aid next
year, the normal penalty for cultivating 10 per cent too much land, an
immediate reduction of only 1 per cent will be imposed. As for the excess
land, the Commission says 10 per cent must be taken out of production next
year, 20 per cent in 1995, 50 per cent in 1996 and 100 per cent in 1997.
The Commission's concession will cost an extra Ecu85m (Pounds 66m) to an
Ecu36bn farm budget already in danger of exceeding its legal ceiling.
Germany responded on Friday by saying it would not respect this compromise,
and would compensate its farmers for any penalties from national funds.
Bonn says the original calculation of the 'base area' in east Germany, made
by Brussels in 1992, was incorrect, by failing to include some 180,000
hectares of land devoted to maize.
Mr Jochen Borchert, the German agriculture minister, said Brussels had
failed to allow for the upheaval in east German agriculture. Far more land
was taken out of use for livestock production than had been forecast, and
the land was switched to cereal production, which was unexpected. 'The very
survival of many farms in east Germany will be at stake,' he said.
Although Chancellor Helmut Kohl has written to Commission president Mr
Jacques Delors defending Germany's case, Brussels regards this posture as an
infraction of EC law.
If the dispute is not resolved, legal action could result, and the
Commission says it will claw back any illicit German aid at the end-of-year
clearing of accounts.
Border controls, Page 2 Editorial Comment, Page 17 Sowing seeds of doubt,
Page 19
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>DEZ  Germany, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
