<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Recovery indicator falters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE financial health of British industry is showing renewed signs of
weakness, says a leading firm of risk assessors, Tony Jackson writes.
The setback adds to concerns about the strength of the economic recovery
raised by recent official statistics.
Syspas, the London-based consultants, said there was a sharp deterioration
in the position of quoted industrial companies in the three months to the
end of August.
The Syspas method is based on analysing published accounts to establish the
risk of financial failure. It first gave warning of recession at the start
of 1989. It first signalled recovery at the end of last year. The position
then remained static until the latest deterioration.
Mr Guenter Steinitz, Syspas's chief executive, said the distribution sector
and smaller unquoted companies continued to show improvement.
This was consistent with recent statistics showing growth in retail sales
and a reduction in the level of bankruptcies, which tend to be concentrated
among small companies.
'The same improvement has not been seen in the major industrial sector,' he
said.
