<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Managers say recession still on
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR managers believe that Britain's recession is not over, an Institute
of Management survey says today. It indicates that most managers do not
believe the recession will end next year.
'This is a disturbing survey,' Mr Roger Young, institute director-general,
said yesterday. 'It shows that managers have not registered recovery despite
the government's claims.'
As many as three out of four managers in the survey of 600 said they did not
believe the recession would end in 1994 while only 3 per cent said it would
be over by December this year. Sixty per cent added that they thought
Britain would dip into further recession during the course of next year.
While 60 per cent of the sample said they had cut jobs, 41 per cent added
they were giving top priority to keeping down the number of workers they
employed. Senior managers laid the blame for Britain's continuing economic
troubles on government policy while on in three blamed the banks, 14 per
cent the European Community and 4 per cent the unions.
Meanwhile, Unison, the public service union, said yesterday that its latest
Jobwatch survey suggested that as many as 20,000 jobs were at risk in the
health service and local government. 'All the signs are that the
government's much-vaunted myth of recovery has evaporated into thin air,'
said Mr Alan Jinkinson, general secretary.
A sharp decline in exports caused almost entirely by the downturn in
continental Europe has been offset by improving home markets, says a survey
of the third quarter of the year by the nine north-west England chambers of
commerce, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
The chambers warn, however, that any recovery is 'still quite delicate' and
next month's Budget must support it by avoiding 'any measures which might
put further economic improvement at risk'.
The fragility of the upturn is shown by the fact that only about 20 per cent
of companies are working at full capacity, the survey of 641 companies says.
The proportion of those working at three-quarters capacity improved, but
only from 74 per cent to 76 per cent.
With so much capacity to spare, the bulk of companies have little appetite
for investment, although there has been a steady upward trend in the last
four quarters from a low base. The balance of manufacturing investment - the
difference between companies increasing and those decreasing spending - was
22 per cent compared with 8 per cent a year ago. Trends in recruitment
showed a slow but steady pick-up in manufacturing in the third quarter.
Although the balance figure of manufacturers recruiting more staff was only
11 per cent, it is the third positive figure in a row after nine quarters of
net labour-shedding between 1990 and the beginning of this year.
Recruitment in the service sector produced a positive balance figure of 18
per cent from 11 per cent in the first and second quarters and 4 per cent in
the last quarter of 1992.
Optimism is increasing among companies in southern England, but their
counterparts in the north and Midlands are less hopeful, a survey released
today says.
Sixty per cent of companies in the south expect sales to increase over the
next three months compared with 53 per cent in the Midlands and 49 per cent
in the north, according to an Enterprise Barometer survey released by 3i,
the venture capital group.
</TEXT>
