<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Tradition revived in W Sussex
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REAL ALE enthusiasts Mr Stephen Lowson and Mr John Ryan have revived the
brewing tradition in Arundel, the picturesque West Sussex town, Philip
Rawstorne writes.
In 1992, 50 years after the closure of Arundel's last brewery, they started
commercial beer production at a site on a nearby industrial estate.
Mr Lowson says: 'Demand for real ale was growing, but nobody was making a
local brew. We saw the opportunity to get into a niche market and took it.'
They bought their equipment second-hand from a northern brewer. 'But
starting up was quite expensive,' Mr Lowson says. 'We spent Pounds 30,000 on
600 casks alone.' But he adds, 'We are now operating at about 75 per cent of
capacity, producing about 400 gallons a day, and supplying about 60 pubs in
the area.' The partners are now expanding into pub ownership.
