FT  18 OCT 93 / Prescott tipped for shadow promotion
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PRESCOTT, shadow transport secretary, is being widely tipped for
promotion to an important economic portfolio after the parliamentary Labour
party's annual election of members of the shadow cabinet on Wednesday.
Mr Prescott - fifth in last year's poll - is one of a number of front-bench
spokesmen from the party's soft left who are expected to attract more
support from their fellow MPs than in the last such election in July 1992.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, and Mr David Blunkett,
shadow health secretary, are also expected to win more votes. Mr Tom Clarke,
shadow Scottish secretary, Mr Ron Davies, shadow Welsh secretary, and Mr
David Clark, shadow defence secretary, are thought the most likely to be
voted out.
Mrs Ann Taylor, shadow education secretary, is also expected to see a
decline in her support after a lacklustre year. But she stands to benefit
from a new requirement obliging MPs to include four women in their 18
nominations, up from three last year.
The 18 MPs securing the most votes in this week's ballot are each guaranteed
a shadow cabinet place, but Mr Smith has full authority in the allocation of
portfolios.
There is greater uncertainty than usual about the election outcome because
the 69 Labour MPs who entered parliament in 1992 will for the first time be
voting after prolonged exposure to those standing.
