FT  18 OCT 93 / Molyneaux says Hume-Adams initiative 'lunacy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JAMES MOLYNEAUX, leader of the Ulster Unionist party, said yesterday that
if the IRA ends its military campaign, a 'quarantine' period of 'years
rather than months' would be necessary before the party would sit at the
same table as Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA.
Speaking in a BBC interview he described as 'sheer lunacy' the Hume-Adams
peace initiative, which he said has the objective of bringing about a
British withdrawal from Northern Ireland within 25 to 30 years.
Mr John Hume, the leader of the Social Democratic and Labour party, who
together with Mr Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, launched the peace
initiative three weeks ago, said that Mr Molyneaux had missed the point of
the initiative. He said its aim was 'a total cessation of all violence . . .
Mr Adams and I have not agreed a plan to impose upon anyone. It is a peace
process which will involve both governments and all parties . . . we have no
specific proposals for a solution.'
Divisions over the peace initiative emerged within the UUP at its party
conference in Craigavon at the weekend. The most contentious question was
whether there should be talks with the government of the Irish Republic,
which is supporting the initiative.
Mr Ken Maginnis, the deputy party leader, said: 'It is important that the
unionist position is very clearly articulated. If Dick Spring (the Irish
foreign minister) is willing to hear that, we are willing to give it to him
at first hand.'
Last week the Irish Foreign Ministry said it has extended invitations to
unionist leaders for discussions and was 'very much looking forward to a
meeting'.
But Mr Molyneaux said yesterday: 'It is not the appropriate time for
face-to-face meetings with Dublin.'
He said that for now he preferred 'quiet communications' through documents
and letters, and confirmed that 'updates on our posi-tion' have been
forwarded to Dublin.
