<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Managers gloomy over recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S senior managers believe that the country is not yet out of
recession and as many as two-thirds do not believe it will be over next
year, Robert Taylor writes.
This gloomy message is contained in the Institute of Management's latest
survey of managerial opinion, published today.
Mr Roger Young, the institute's director-general, yesterday said: 'It shows
that managers have not registered recovery despite the government's claims.'
As many as three out of four managers in the survey of 600 said they did not
believe the recession would end in 1994 while only 3 per cent said it would
be over by December this year.
Sixty per cent said they thought Britain would dip into further recession
during the course of next year.
While 60 per cent of the sample said they had cut jobs, 41 per cent added
they were giving top priority to keeping down the number of workers they
employed.
Unison, the public service union , said its latest jobwatch survey suggested
as many as 20,000 jobs were at risk in the health service and local
government sector.
