<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Gas price rise may broaden market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT CORZINE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDEPENDENT gas companies say British Gas's decision last week to raise
prices by as much as 12.5 per cent to some large industrial customers could
open up limited opportunities in the interruptible market, which until now
has failed to attract competitors, Robert Corzine writes.
Interruptible consumers, which typically use gas for power generation at
large industrial sites, pay low prices but risk being cut off during periods
of peak demand, when many are able temporarily to use oil or other fuels.
Kinetica, a joint venture between PowerGen and Conoco, said it 'sees some
value in the interruptible market', while United Gas, the UK arm of
Utilicorp of the US, believes 'a handful of opportunities could arise'.
The British Gas price rises range from 2.1 per cent to 12.5 per cent,
depending on the volume of gas purchased, and cover three-year to 10-year
contracts signed on or after November 2. Existing contracts or companies
seeking shorter-term arrangements will not be affected.
The independent gas companies contend that true competition in the
interruptible segment will not occur until the full domestic market is
opened up. They will need to use it as British Gas does, as a way to shift
supplies quickly to smaller commercial and residential consumers at times of
peak demand.
</TEXT>
