<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Thatcher wades into defence budget debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARONESS THATCHER, the former prime minister, yesterday waded into the
heated debate over the defence budget, issuing a blunt warning against
further deep cuts in spending on the eve of a two-day Commons defence
debate.
Interviewed on BBC TV's Breakfast with Frost, Lady Thatcher steered clear of
specific references to the current cabinet dispute but argued that to
'weaken your defence below a certain level is very dangerous'.
'That after all is what we did between World War One and World War Two,' she
said. 'There are still aggressors in the world, we have seen it from
Serbia.' She continued: 'The only way to make certain that we can beat a
tyrant whenever he shows his hand is to keep your defences strong.
'The great thing about President Reagan, President Bush and myself was,
whatever we had to do, we never had to think 'have we got the equipment, the
trained men, or the latest missiles?' because wise foresight had seen to it
that we had.'
Her remarks came as Sir Nicholas Bonsor, Conservative chairman of the
cross-party Commons defence committee, wrote to Mr John Major, the prime
minister, saying that further cuts would put Britain's armed forces under an
unacceptable level of stress.
Such actions are part of a strong rearguard action launched by opponents of
further defence cuts in response to the Treasury's targeting of the Ministry
of Defence's Pounds 23.5bn budget in this year's public spending round.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, has demanded a full-scale review
of Britain's armed forces if the Treasury refuses to drop its demands for
more cuts.
Mr Rifkind is expected to use this week's debate - at which several Tory
backbenchers will voice their opposition to further cuts - to announce the
shelving of plans for a new nuclear missile for the Royal Air Force which
would have cost up to Pounds 3bn.
He is also expected to outline the government's views on the future of the
royal dockyards including moves towards private-sector ownership.
In her Frost interview, Lady Thatcher served notice that the rightwing tone
of the Conservative party conference had helped to put Mr Major back in her
good books.
His speech to the party conference this month had led to a 'sea change' in
her attitude towards him, she explained. 'Thatcherism is alive and well. I
believe that was confirmed very much by the prime minister's speech at the
party conference which was back to fundamental principles.'
</TEXT>
