<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Israel to free most Palestinian prisoners
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL'S foreign minister Mr Shimon Peres said yesterday he expected most of
the 11,000 Palestinians held in Israeli prisons would be released, agencies
report.
PLO officials have said their release would help build Palestinian support
for the peace accord. Most of the prisoners are accused of taking part in
the six-year uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
'I think the large majority (of prisoners) will be released since
circumstances have changed, the reasons for their detention and arrest have
vanished or changed. Our position also needs a change,' Mr Peres said on
army radio.
The intention to release prisoners was confirmed by Prime Minister Yitzhak
Rabin. He told Israel radio: 'We certainly will come to the freeing of
prisoners. Not just one here and there, but big numbers.' The next round of
Middle East peace talks has been delayed after Syria threatened to stay
away, an Israeli official said yesterday. Syria, which reacted coolly to
last month's Israel-PLO peace deal, has complained the Palestinians are not
co-ordinating moves with Arab states and Israel is preoccupied with the
Palestinian issue.
