<HEADLINE>
FT  18 OCT 93 / Paying with cash costs UK consumers Pounds 800m a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT COSTS the British Pounds 800m a year in lost interest income to carry
around banknotes and coins in wallets and handbags, according to a study of
the costs of circulating cash around the economy.
The first detailed study for 20 years estimates that it costs Pounds 4.5bn
to lubricate the Pounds 250bn flow of cash payments made in Britain each
year.
Individuals pay Pounds 800m, with a further Pounds 800m from shops and
business, Pounds 700m from the Post Office and Pounds 2.2bn from the Bank of
England and commercial banks.
The study, carried out by the Boston Consulting Group for De La Rue, the
banknote printer, estimates that the use of cash costs each of Britain's 22m
households Pounds 210 a year in lost interest and handling expenses.
Each household holds an average of Pounds 460 in cash at any one time, it
estimates. The figure is thought to be so high because it is artificially
boosted by the 'black economy' of unregistered and criminal enterprises
which deal largely in cash.
The cost of the cash-handling system has quadrupled since the last detailed
analysis in 1973, when it was estimated at Pounds 540m at 1992 prices.
Handling cash now costs each commercial bank between Pounds 200m and Pounds
300m a year.
One reason for the rapid escalation in costs of cash handling is that
automated teller machines (ATMs) installed over the past two decades have
made it easier to obtain cash, and so increased the strain on the cash
distribution system. Since 1975, ATM cash withdrawals have quadrupled, while
bank counter withdrawals have declined only slightly.
Mr Simon Farmbrough, a Boston Consulting Group vice-president, said banks
could reduce costs by improved automation and analysis of cash handling.
'There is potential to drive down costs quite significantly.'
The finding that the average household held Pounds 460 in cash had been
checked with financial institutions because it appeared so high, he said.
'It is clear that some of that money is being carried around in suitcases,'
Mr Farmbrough said.
The study follows an analysis by the banks' Association for Payments and
Clearing Services earlier this year, which found that cheque and cash
clearing costs banks about Pounds 4.5bn a year, of which about half is the
cost of cash handling.
This agrees with the Boston Consulting study, which estimates the cost of
cash handling for banks at Pounds 1.9bn, with another Pounds 300m in forgone
interest. The Pounds 800m cost for businesses is half handling expenses, and
half forgone interest.
The study estimates, however, that in spite of the costs, Britain's
cash-handling system is cheaper than the system in either France or Germany.
Cash mountain haunts banks Page 9
</TEXT>
<XX>
