<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 93 / Clinton blockades Haiti to back UN sanctions: Troops on
standby to protect Americans on island
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday ordered a naval blockade of Haiti to
enforce renewed United Nations sanctions due to take effect on Monday and
placed on standby an 'enhanced' infantry company at the Guantanamo base in
nearby Cuba.
He also revoked the US visas and froze the US financial assets of all those
identified as preventing the agreed return of Fr Jean-Bertrand Aristide, the
ousted president.
The naval task force of six warships - the first was to be on station last
night and the rest today - is under orders to intercept any commercial
shipping suspected of trying to break the oil and arms embargo. Acting in
advance of an expected UN Security Council resolution authorising 'military
power' to enforce the embargo, Mr Clinton advised merchant ships to give the
destroyers 'a very wide berth'.
Mr Clinton had hinted on Thursday he might impose a naval cordon, an action
rendered more probable by the murder later in the day of the justice
minister in the interim government in Port-au-Prince. Yesterday he conceded
it was a 'blockade' - if not in the full legal meaning of the word, in
'common sense parlance'.
Asked if the infantry force might be used to evacuate the 1,000 Americans
now in Haiti, Mr Clinton replied he wanted the troops 'in a position to deal
with any contingencies that might arise'.
'There are important American interests at stake in Haiti,' he said,
including the safety of Americans and the promotion of democracy.
The naval deployment bears some resemblance to the Cuban missile blockade of
1962 ordered by President John Kennedy. Yesterday Congressman Joseph
Kennedy, JFK's nephew and close to Fr Aristide, was among several to demand
action.
In Port-au-Prince, UN special envoy Dante Caputo said most of the UN
civilian mission to monitor human rights would leave for the Dominican
Republic last night and today. Two pro-military groups demanded that all
white foreigners immediately leave the country, independent local radio
reported.
Torn in the USA, Page 9
</TEXT>
