<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow fails to consolidate
morning gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER POSTING strong early gains on higher bond prices and good inflation
news, US stocks lost ground during the afternoon amid expirations-related
selling to end a busy session only slightly firmer, writes Patrick Harverson
in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 8.10 at 3,629.76,
below its high for the day of 3,642.30. Other indices set new record highs
for the second straight day. The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500
ended up 2.67 at 469.50, the Amex composite up 1.58 at 483.23, and the
Nasdaq composite up 2.02 at 787.43. Trading volume on the NYSE was 360m
shares.
Following Thursday's good news on producer prices, which rose only 0.2 per
cent in September, it was the turn yesterday of the consumer prices data to
cheer up bond and stock markets.
The labor department reported that its consumer prices index was unchanged
last month, and that 'core' consumer prices (excluding the volatile food and
energy components) rose by only 0.1 per cent.
Both sets of data pleased fixed-income investors, and lifted bond prices
sharply. The benchmark 30-year issue rose almost a full point, lowering the
yield to 5.781 per cent.
The good news on inflation, and the subsequent decline in bond yields,
lifted stock prices in turn. Some positive quarterly earnings reports from
leading companies also helped prices and sentiment. Prices slipped back in
the mid-afternoon, however, on selling related to the monthly expiration of
derivatives contracts, before recovering slightly at the end. Among
individual stocks, technology issues were in demand. Texas Instruments,
which has been moving up and down lately in line with the fluctuating
fortunes of the semiconductor stocks, jumped Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 65 3/4
after the company announced a big improvement in third quarter earnings to
Dollars 146m.
Also higher in the sector were IBM, up Dollars 1 7/8 at Dollars 44 5/8 ,
Hewlett-Packard, up Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 70 1/8 , and Motorola, Dollars
1 5/8 firmer at Dollars 106.
Kellogg jumped Dollars 3 1/4 to Dollars 56 after the foods group unveiled
quarterly profits of Dollars 209m, up from Dollars 199.7m a year earlier and
above analysts' forecasts.
Navistar International was the NYSE's most heavily traded stock, rising
Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 23 in volume of 8m shares after the truck and
diesel engine manufacturing company issued 22m new shares of its common
stock at Dollars 21 7/8 .
On the Nasdaq market, Apple Computer climbed Dollars 4 1/2 to Dollars 28 1/4
in volume of 8.5m shares after the company announced a fiscal fourth quarter
profit of 2 cents a share and said Mr John Sculley, its long-time chairman,
was resigning. Mr Sculley's departure had been expected.
Canada
A WAVE of positive sentiment swept Toronto stocks to a sharply higher close
and pushed the TSE-300 index to a record level. It closed 37.62 points up at
4,182.58 in turnover of 60.7m shares valued at CDollars 765m.
Earlier it hadreached 4,183.82, breaching Thursday's intraday record high.
Toronto's key index rose 2.8 percent in four days.
</TEXT>
