<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 93 / Money Markets: Rate cut pressure grows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN short-term interest rate futures continued to push upwards
yesterday, signalling the belief that interest rates are due to slide,
writes Peter John.
December short sterling and D-Mark contracts traded on Liffe were both
strong and the French contract traded on the Matif in Paris rose 10 basis
points in early trade.
The contracts go up on expectation of lower rates. They reflect the market's
view of where three-month lending rates are moving ahead of the contract
maturity dates in December.
Short sterling has been firm all week and appears to have broken through a
narrow trading range as belief solidifies that the UK government must cut
base rates by at least half a point if the economy is to continue its
recovery. The short sterling futures contract for December moved through
94.50 to close 12 basis points up at 94.57.
There is also a growing body of opinion that some European countries,
especially France and Belgium, will be forced to abandon attempts to link
their currencies with the D-Mark by cutting rates and letting them find
their own level.
The French financial futures contract rose 14 basis points to 93.56 while
the much more thinly traded Belgian contract added to a big rise on Thursday
with a further 26-basis point rise to 91.51. That level indicated
three-month money would be around 8.5 per cent in December. The Belgian
three-month rate was at 10 per cent yesterday. The German D-Mark contract
rose 4 basis points to 93.84.
Bank of England operations were relatively comfortable yesterday. The Bank
offered the money market an early round of assistance after forecasting a
liquidity shortage of around Pounds 1.5bn which was later revised down to
Pounds 1.3bn.
Among the main factors affecting the market were the take-up of Treasury
Bills and paper maturing in official hands which drained Pounds 504m from
the system, Exchequer transactions which removed Pounds 445m and a rise in
note circulation which took up another Pounds 675m.
Partly offsetting these developments were bankers' balances above target
which injected Pounds 145m into the system.
The central bank bought Pounds 1.004bn of bills at the early round of
assistance followed by a further Pounds 81m and late assistance of Pounds
110m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
