<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 93 / UK Company News: Hi-Tec chiefs unwind US options
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR EXECUTIVES at Hi-Tec, the sports shoe and leisure wear group, are being
paid Pounds 2.5m in cash and shares to unwind their original options over
the company's US business.
Hi-Tec yesterday announced details of a complicated deal which it said would
free the company to seek an efficient equity injection for its rapidly
growing US business.
The four executives - including main board director Mr Terry Mackness who
joined the US operation in 1988 - have options over 13 per cent of Hi-Tec
Sports USA.
Mr Peter Butler, finance director, said that under the original agreement
their stakes could not be diluted. This meant that the directors would have
to be paid a proportion of any equity injection into the US business.
'We agreed with the management that they should exercise their options now,'
Mr Butler said. The value of their stake at the option price is Dollars
1.6m, valuing the US business at Dollars 30m (Pounds 19.8m).
However, the executives have agreed to sell back 8.5 per cent of the 13 per
cent stake for Dollars 2.6m in cash and the issue of 1.4m shares in the
parent company. They will receive Dollars 1.6m in cash, offsetting the cost
of exercising the options.
Three of the four executives will also receive a 3 per cent stake in the
quoted parent as payment, while one US director has opted for a deferred
cash sum of Dollars 1m.
The executives will then be granted options over a further 6.5 per cent in
the US business, exercisable in three years at a total cost of Dollars 3.6m.
Mr Butler said this valued the US business at Dollars 44m.
Hi-Tec's shares closed 2p lower at 60p, for a market value of Pounds 28m.
</TEXT>
